Shared Risk Link Group (SRLG) is an important concept from survivable optical. An SRLG is a group of network links that share a common physical resource (cable, conduit, node or substructure),whose failure will cause the failure of all links of the group [Papadimitriou et al., 2001 ].Typical optical network architecture can be classified into two layers: optical layer and physical layer,which are shown in Fig. 1. The physical layer includes fiber spans(e.g. cable, conduit. etc.), optical switch nodes (e.g. OADM,1 OXC2) and fiber span nodes (i.e. locations where fiber spans terminate).The optical layer consists of links and optical switch nodes(a subset of the nodes in the physical layer). A "link" in the
optical layer is a connection in the physical layer, which may traverse over several fiber spans and/or fiber span nodes. Also,
several such links may pass through the same fiber span and fiber span node. The multiple links that pass through the same fiber
span constitute an SRLG. A single failure such as a fiber span cut in the physical layer can cause multiple link failures.

