Problem: Disjoint paths(DP) problem:
    Give a directed network G=($\mathbb{N,L}$)of a set $\mathbb{N}$ of N nodes and a set $\mathbb{L}$ of L weighted links,two special node s,t$\in$ $\mathbb{N}$,and a integer k$\geq$0,Find k paths $P_1$,$P_2$,...,$P_k$ from s to t,such that the paths share no common links(nodes,SRLG and SRNG).

Additional conditions could also be imposed on the disjoint paths, such as:

\begin{itemize}
 \item Min-max disjoint paths problem - the sum of the weights of all the constituent links of the path with the largest path weight is minimized.
 \item Min-min disjoint paths problem - the sum of the weights of all the constituent links of the path with the smallest path weight is minimized.
 \item Bounded disjoint paths problem - the sum of the weights of all the constituent links of each path should each be less than D.
 \item Min-sum disjoint paths problem - the sum of the weights of all the constituent links of the k paths is minimized.
\end{itemize}

The min-min condition is NP-hard to solve [ L. Guo and H. Shen, “On finding min min disjoint paths,” Algorithmica, vol. 66, no. 3, pp. 641C653, 2013. ], and to be
approximated within a factor of e for any constant e > 1 [D. Xu, Y. Chen, Y. Xiong, C. Qiao, and X. He, “On
the complexity of and algorithms for finding the shortest path with a disjoint counterpart,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Netw., vol. 14, no. 1, pp. 147C158, 2006.].
The min-min condition is useful when only one path is active and used by traffic, while the other k>1 paths remain idle as backups. Only when an active path fails will one of the backup paths be activated to substitute the active path. Hence, the active path should have as minimal weight as possible, since the active path is used more frequently than the backup paths.

