\subsection{Basic Idea}
\label{subsec:Basic Idea}
We will first explain the basic concept of CSLE before describing the algorithm detailed.So the problem of finding a SRNG(shared risk node group)-disjoint path can be transformed to the problem of finding a SRLG-disjoint path by splitting each node of shared risk node group into two halves with a “virtual” zero-cost directed link,which of them are belong the same Shared Risk Link Group when they is from the same SRNG(shared risk node group),and an undirected link can be represented as two directed links,we will use the example of finding two-disjoint paths in a directed network shown in \ref{fig:Initial Graph}, to illustrate the intuition behind our CSLE heuristic. In \ref{fig:Initial Graph} The shortest AP found so far is shown in dotted line for which no SRLG-disjoint BP exists.
In \ref{fig:Initial Graph},there are four shared risk link groups.as follows, the links \{S-1,S-2\} is the first shared risk link group. the links \{2-3,5-d\} is the second shared risk link group. the links \{3-8,3-4,9-4\} is the third shared risk link group. the links \{4-5,5-7\} is the forth shared risk link group.

For a given AP,we define its Conflicting SRLG(Shared Risk Link Group) Link Set $\mathbb{T}$ to be a subset of the links on the AP such that any AP using all these “problematic”fffffffff links cannot find a SRLG-disjoint BP. Although together all the links along AP form such a conflicting SRLG link set, we are interested in a set having as few as possible. For example in \ref{fig:Initial Graph} $\mathbb{T}$ can be {2->3,3->4,4->5},{e1,e2,e3}.Later, we will describe an algorithm to find T and prove that if any AP uses all the links ffffffff in this T, no SRLG-disjoint BP can be found. Note that, it is possible that an AP using all but one link in T can still have a BP.

\subsection{Divided-and-conquer}
Now, we will make use of the Conflicting SRLG(Shared Risk Link Group) Link Set $\mathbb{T}$ to divide-and-conquer the Min-Min SRLG-Disjoint Problem. More specifically, let (the inclusion set $\mathbb{I}$)and(the exclusion set $\mathbb{O}$) be two disjoint subsets of $\mathbb{E}$. Denoted by $\mathbb{P(I,O)}$) the subproblem (of the Min-Min SRLG-Disjoint Problem) of finding a pair of AP and BP, where the AP is the shortest among all possible APs that must use the links in $\mathbb{I}$ but not the links in $\mathbb{O}$. Then, the (original) Min-Min SRLG-Disjoint Problem can be represented by $\mathbb{P{\emptyset,\emptyset}}$.
Note that, for any given link, the solution to $\mathbb{P{\emptyset,\emptyset}}$, if exists at all, will use an AP that either contains the link or not. Accordingly, for the example in \ref{fig:Initial Graph}, can be divided into two subproblems $\mathbb{P{\emptyset,e_1}}$ and $\mathbb{P{e_1,\emptyset}}$, Similarly, $\mathbb{P{{e_1},\emptyset}}$ can be further divided into two subproblems $\mathbb{P{{e_1,e_2},\emptyset}}$ and $\mathbb{P{{e_1},{e_2}}}$,$\mathbb{P{{e_l,e_2},\emptyset}}$ can be further divided into two subproblems $\mathbb{P{{e_l,e_2,e_3},\emptyset}}$ and $\mathbb{P{{e_l,e_2},{e_3}}}$. The concept of the conflicting shared risk link set T comes handy because there is no need to consider $\mathbb{P{{e_l,e_2,e_3},\emptyset}}$ which we know has no solution.

We will try to find an optimal solution to each of the two subproblems $\mathbb{P{\emptyset,{e_1}}}$ and $\mathbb{P{{e_1},\emptyset}}$, and then select the better one (i.e., the path pair with the shorter AP) to be the final (optimal) solution to the original problem . If there is no
solution to any of the two subproblems, we can guarantee that there is no solution to the original problem, simply because of the way in which the problem was divided. Note that, each subproblem can be solved in a similar divide-and-conquer way. In addition, in a subproblem, such as $\mathbb{P{\emptyset,{e_1}}}$, even though we have excluded a conflicting SRLG(shared risk link group)link set from AP,it is possible that the new (shortest) AP found still does not have a SRLG-disjoint BP. In such a case, we will find a new conflicting SRLG(shared risk link group) link set for this new AP, based on which the subproblem can be further divided into several sub-subproblems, until either a solution is found for a sub-subproblem, or no AP can be found for this sub-subproblem due to a large number of excluded conflicting links from this sub-subproblem.

In general, given a conflicting SRLG(shared risk link group) link set $|T|=\{e_1,e_2,\cdots,e|T|\}$, the original Min-Min problem can be first divided into the following subproblems,$\mathbb{P{\emptyset,{e_1}}}$,$\mathbb{P{{e_1},{e_2}}}$,$\cdots$,$\mathbb{P{{e_1,e_2,\dots,e_{|T|-1}},{e_{|T|}}}}$.In other words, the number of subproblems to be solved is equal to $\mathbb{T}$, (This is why we want to have a small set of  $\mathbb{T}$). Speaking of complexity, it should take us less time to solve each subproblem than the original problem itself as at least one link (which is a conflicting SRLG(shared risk link group) link ) will be removed from any further path computation for an AP, which also ensures that a different AP will be found and tested for the existence of a link-disjoint BP. In practice, such a divide-and-conquer approach based on the exclusion of conflicting SRLG(shared risk link group) links can yield an optimal solution fast, and in fact, faster than any existing approaches such as KSP, as will be shown later.



